A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interior of Gaudi
The roof is like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish mules.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was named "Bone House."
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splits and mosaics, which remind of scales of facades and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of the youth style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only when you see more clearly that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-through order.
During the night, the whole facade is even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting strengthens the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and entangled forms also control the interior of the house.
Wavy shaped wood copies the window frames, railing, decorative elements of doors, even holes and bars.
The House Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia no. 43 was created by the conversion of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese performed.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed to the idea of Gaudís for an unusual and even cheaper conversion.
The Casa Batlló rental house, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner and the use of mosaics on the façade were created on his board.
However, many other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the draft Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
For example, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after it was completed, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Bone House."
Others in turn called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "looking house."
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system, unique for the time being, with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
A little bizarre already mutates her 45-degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations at the time and was not allowed to be accompanied by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so disappointed at the result that they asked for help.
Among other things, the Council's leaders also met with the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, on the contrary - only 15 days after the request of the district in this respect, Josep Batlló made an application to authorise the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was given to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social lounge, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion removed all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salondoors, so a larger society could easily chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house was given a rather unusual roof and two other floors, in addition to a new façade, by Gaudí's conversion.
It is also impressive to play Gaudís with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the courts of light.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the World Heritage List of Unesco in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and beautiful apartment is made available to the public.
The house owners only decided to take this step in the year on the occasion of the 150.birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this is a quite one-off business, the visits were kept, but they were also extended to other common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the building is not a piece of paper, it is 16.50 Euro, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist certificates get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
