A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of suffering from prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the cancer research institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should be subject to a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stress, Mrs Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
For more than half of the participants in the study, the right hand index finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was observed as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were equal.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33%, and in men up to 60 even by 87%.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which already form in the prenatal age, clearly reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
