The discovery of a foreign bacterial species, which can live, among other things, from arsenic, opens up new opportunities for new forms of life on earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is in their view a sign that life is possible even without the elements considered necessary to life.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it something very special, although it is almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears on Thursday in the online edition of the Science magazine.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in the California Mono Lake is growing even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"It is a question of what else is possible," said the co-author of the Ariel D. Anbar report from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, says Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could act on the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems organisms can start biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily defined," said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," added Cockell.
This discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake due to the high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, it assumed that microbes exposed to both may replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to the chemical nature of it as phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for the organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. It comes into our biochemical system, where it almost lubricates everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can naturally occur, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a microbiology lecturer at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has been no working example yet.
Arsen was more common in the early years of the earth, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have developed differently than in the early age of the earth," says Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
