As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will comply with the required penalty at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but in this sport-followed rules.
Part of the upcoming debate on the present case is that a team of the Real Madrid Football Club (who preached in his hymn of nobility and honor and had punished his players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the main role in this, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this practice, which is not explicitly forbidden by the Statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts are a rule circumventing. Indeed, this approach is in keeping with the Statutes of sport, but it seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused by the sport spirit should be examined.
The spirit of sport defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not threatened by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the opposing players from taking an unjustified advantage of the counter-team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by a misplay or a delusion, because the circumference of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and took the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the aggressors draw from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was not put in a less favourable position, nor were the benefits of the game to be played, because the obvious result of this action was that its own team had to continue playing with less players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is, obviously, that the players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually be eliminated. In addition, the players will receive a penalty with this approach and pass into the second card cycle, in which they will leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to the accumulation of a card.
This does not make it so clear whether this is really an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the sport spirit, which includes strategic decisions in order to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a penalty (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumference), they wanted to choose when they were subject to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or escaping from it.
Although the limit between the gift of invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of the gift of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics were created as a result of two factors: because they were two self-exclusion and because of the type of provocative rule transfer.
The damage that has been done to the principles of sport through these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
