Global plan for the renewal of lighting
The UN yesterday in Cancun proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs), which is close to one third of the additional reduction to be achieved in order to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the major concrete projects which the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from the developed countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to the earth due to the lighting if the white-burning pears, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better, by light-emitting diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the global fleet's exhaust gases.
In Copenhagen last year, large exhaust gas issuers such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global emissions of CFCs from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it would be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the 2-degree increase in climate from today to 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing pears, 95% of the energy in the form of heat is released, and the remaining 5% are producing the light.
With the compact light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LED light bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice again.
The compact light bulbs hold on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those put on the market this week by the manufacturer Philips - this society, by the way, has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white light bulb, which is an indication of the potential savings of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that this completely new light bulbs give very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact light bulbs have reserves, because they contain mercury and that they have to be disposed of as a special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for producers providing a place of acceptance.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which cause much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants produce 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
