Climate: how France speaks its financial promises beautifully
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the fast-track financing promises (also called "fast start" or early financing) that have been implemented by developing countries.
And the coarse French beauty-tellers are already exposed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have committed themselves to providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years, France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all the registers to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: the detailed progress report of its Member States, press conference, major side-events, and the distribution of brochures.
The transparency operation is remarkable and is highly appreciated for its real value: the developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which will bring it on the right track to pay for its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look into the detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional commitment has been made without reaching the detriment of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guide value that he considers best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen itself as a benchmark for those in 2009: international financing will be maintained and will provide 150 million in the framework of the "fast-start" funding for over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar indicative values, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France considered that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional."
In other words, there are no indicative figures for the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
In concrete terms, the overall amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France states that it will comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another key element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about it yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, are €1 loaned as equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often linked to the reduction of emissions, which is based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is fraudulent to present the euro that is taken as an equivalent to a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the capital country should be considered as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing other than the following thinking: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by borrowing 91.5% (EUR 389.8 million) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is calling for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) are 100% committed to donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union is spending €1 to fulfil its obligations, France is giving only 10 cents and means a similar commitment.
Nice hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double flaw: in part with a further development of the action over time and in part with the reality of financial use.
France succeeds in making it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving EUR 36.1 million.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once in the EU (why do the other Member States continue to lend if it is enough?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely mistaken...
The chapter of early financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the whole of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machine of the UNFCCC.
