Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years takes on different chemical substances over the day 81, such a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of coming generations).
The association, which explains that its results "do not reflect statistically significant value in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem," had bought between July and September the usual food consumed by a approximately ten-year-old child at meals plus an intermediate meal in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and vegetables, three milk products and 1.5 litres of water per day - have been examined as well as rodents of laboratories looking for chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is degrading: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or likely to be carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine impairment, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the near whole of the cases, this survey is very well understood that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptive factors is worrying," the Association notes.
At breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely known as carcinogens, as well as more than twenty residues that may affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, which is intended to be used as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study has found traces of an insecticide that is strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the hacksteak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were also injected.
The analysis has revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform in the tap water.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 chemical residues was the "richest," and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is likely to be underestimated," the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has in turn proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civil diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
